english:
  title: A Preface on Drinking from Lotus Vessels
  author: Lee Cham
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the Seuwoon Quarter where I dwell, the lotus pods have ripened. Playing with a blade, I carved into them and discovered within their chambers shapes most curious—some angular like goblets, others round like bells—each a perfect vessel for wine.

    Cleaning away the tangled fibers that clung within, I filled them with wine and drank. How pure, how fragrant! The color itself shone clear and bright. I invited guests and, matching each to a pod suited to their capacity, we raised them together and drank in unison, swaying pleasantly into joy.

    The Jade Tube Drinking of old has long tradition, yet that manner—hand extended, stem grasped, face tilted upward—bears scant resemblance to the ancient rite of offering cup to guest. But hear what I have learned: the ancients observed ceremony through bows and yielding gestures; through ritual washing to attain purity; through reverent prostration to show respect.

    Now behold the lotus vessel: it bows of itself, requiring no gesture of courtesy; its inner surface, untouched by dust, achieves cleanliness without ablution; its hollow form stands straight and true, conveying respect without genuflection. Moreover, its very shape mirrors the drinking vessels of old. Thus to adopt the ancient rites of wine-drinking seems most fitting.

    But those who drink like oxen, who drink perched like birds, who drink low like turtles—all these abandon propriety and indulge in excess. How can they be spoken of in the same breath?

    Remarkable indeed! That no ancients discovered this before me speaks only to the limits of their imagination. That it begins with my hand—is this mere chance?
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'Seuwoon Quarter (Seuwoon-bang): A district in Seoul known for its cultural refinement'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Jade Tube Drinking: An ancient practice of drinking through a bamboo or jade tube from a shared vessel, referenced as an elegant precedent'
  - key: ''
    value: The three vulgar forms of drinking mentioned (ox-drinking, bird-nesting, turtle-drinking) refer to uncouth, inelegant methods condemned in classical texts
